To handle the variable portion of the CSV line with OpenCSV, you can use a custom converter. This converter will be responsible for parsing the variable part of the line and converting it into a list of ContainerProperty objects.

To create a custom converter, you need to implement the CsvConverter interface. This interface has a single method, convert(), which takes a String as input and returns an Object.

In the convert() method, you will need to parse the variable part of the CSV line and convert it into a list of ContainerProperty objects. You can do this by splitting the variable part of the line into pairs of values, and then creating a ContainerProperty object for each pair of values.

Once you have created a custom converter, you need to register it with OpenCSV. You can do this by using the CSVParserBuilder.withConverter() method.

Finally, you need to use the CsvCustomBindByName annotation to bind the variable part of the CSV line to the properties field of your DTO.

Here is an example of a custom converter for parsing the variable part of the CSV line:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: java hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    public class ContainerPropertiesConverter implements CsvConverter {

        @Override
        public Object convert(String value) {
            List&lt;ContainerProperty&gt; properties = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

            String[] pairs = value.split(&quot;;;&quot;);
            for (String pair : pairs) {
                String[] keyValue = pair.split(&quot;;&quot;);
                String key = keyValue[0];
                String value = keyValue[1];

                ContainerProperty property = new ContainerProperty();
                property.setKey(key);
                property.setValue(value);

                properties.add(property);
            }

            return properties;
        }
    }


&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

To register the custom converter with OpenCSV:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: java hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    CSVParserBuilder builder = new CSVParserBuilder();
    builder.withConverter(new ContainerPropertiesConverter());

    CSVParser parser = builder.build();


&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;
 example of how to use the CsvCustomBindByName annotation to bind the variable part of the CSV line to the properties field of your DTO:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: java hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    public class MyDTO {

        @CsvBindByPosition(position = 12, required = true)
        private Double localizationStop;
        @CsvBindByPosition(position = 13, required = false)
        private Double latitudeStop;
        @CsvBindByPosition(position = 14, required = false)
        private Double longitudeStop;

        @CsvCustomBindByName(column = &quot;properties&quot;, converter = ContainerPropertiesConverter.class)
        private List&lt;ContainerProperty&gt; properties;
    }


&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

